Katerina Anghelaki-Rooke. _The Scattered Papers of Penelope: New and Selected Poems_. Edited by Karen Van Dyck. Saint Paul, MN: Graywolf Press, 2009. xix, 123 p.

ISBN 978-1-55597-519-7 (USA)

[In the London edition (London: Anvil Press Poetry, 2008, Ltd. 127 p.; ISBN 978 0 85646 401 0) the pagination is different; it has the following extras: Index of Titles (pp. 121-122), Index of Translators (p. 123), Afterword by the editor (pp. 125-126). It also has footnotes in the Introduction (which are missing in the U.S.A. edition).]

Introduction: "The Island of Return" by Karen Van Dyck (pp. ix-xix);

from the collection _Magdalene, the Vast Mammal_: "The Body Is the Victory and the Defeat of Dreams" [Karen Van Dyck, tr.] (pp. 3-4);

from _The Scattered Papers of Penelope_: "Penelope Says" [Karen Van Dyck, tr.] (pp. 7-8), "Jealousy" [Gail Holst-Warhaft, tr.] (p. 9), "The Suitors" [Karen Van Dyck, tr.] (pp. 10-12);

from _The Triumph of Constant Loss_: "The Triumph of Constant Loss" [Rae Dalven, tr.] (p. 15), from "The Angel Poems": II "Angels are the whores of heaven ..." (p. 16), III "He would emerge ..." (pp. 17-18), V "Before they ripen ..." (p. 19), VII "When an angel grows red ..." (pp. 20-21), "Interlude" (p. 22), VIII "When angels chance to become lovers ..." (p. 23), X "If in nature Being becomes secure ..." (p. 24) [Kimon Friar, tr.];

from _Counter Love_: "I Have a Stone" (p. 27), "Heat" (pp. 28-29) [Katerina Anghelaki Rooke & Jackie Willcox, trs.], "The Cicada" [Gail Holst-Warhaft, tr.], "My Plastic Thing" (p. 31), "Writing" (p. 32) [Katerina Anghelaki Rooke & Jackie Willcox, trs.], "The Little Ladder" [Rae Dalven, tr.] (p. 33), "Matchsticks" [Gail Holst-Warhaft, tr.] (p. 34), "Beings and Things on Their Own" (p. 35), "The Barber Shop" (p. 36) [Katerina Anghelaki Rooke & Jackie Willcox, trs.], "When the Body" (pp. 37-38), "The Spider's Dream" (p. 39), "Sleep" (pp. 40-41) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.];

from _The Suitors_: "The Third Summer, or The Catastrophe" [Gail Holst-Warhaft, tr.] (pp. 45-47);

from _Epilogue Wind_: "The Red Moon" [Karen Van Dyck, tr.] (pp. 51-52), from "The Narrative of the Self": 'the Scar' (pp. 53-54), 'Aegina' (pp. 55-56), 'The Piglet' (p. 57) [Katerina Anghelaki Rooke & Jackie Willcox, trs.], 'Epilogue Wind' (p. 58) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.], "The Wedding" (pp. 59-61) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.], from "Springtime for Yanousa": 'Yanousa Counts Her Belongings' (p. 62), 'The Heroine Contemplates Her Hand' (p. 63), 'The Squirrel to the Woman' (pp. 64-65), 'Monastic' (p. 66), 'Yanousa and a Poem' (p. 67), 'Even Raphael Is Helpless' (p. 68), 'Out of Her Life' (p. 69) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.], "In This House Settling Time's Account" (pp. 70-73) [Katerina Anghelaki Rooke & Jackie Willcox, trs.];

from _Empty Nature_: "War Diary": '13th Day, or Dry land at Last' (p. 77), '14th Day, or The Elimination of the Inner World' (pp. 78-79), '15th Day, or The Lesson' (p. 80), '16th Day, or The End of the Person' (p. 81), '17th Day, or One More Elegy' (p. 82), '18th Day, or The New Order of Things' (p. 83), '19th Day, or What We Know about Sleep' (p. 84), '20th Day, or The Little Phrase' (p. 85), 'Days Later, or The Moral Always in Prose' (p. 86) [Gail Holst-Warhaft, tr.], "Fluffy Things" (p. 87) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.];

from _Flesh Is a Beautiful Desert_: "The Other Penelope" [Edmund & Mary Keeley, trs.] (pp. 91-92), "The Transcription of a Nightmare" (p. 93), "Love-Struck Reptile" (p. 94) [Jane Assimakopoulos, tr.]; _Lipiu_: "Lipiu" [Karen Van Dyck, tr.] (pp. 97-101);

New Poems: "Hush Now, Don't Be Afraid ..." (p. 105), "Matter Alone" (p. 106) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.], "Poetry Guided Me Well (pp. 107-108) [Jane Assimakopoulos, tr.], "Lipiu Once Again" (pp. 109-112), "Translating Life's End into Love" (pp. 113-114) [Karen Van Dyck, tr.].

Notes (pp. 115-116); About the Poet and the Translators (pp. 121-123).

